    name: "Ramones",
    quote: "Gabba Gabba Hey!",
    story: "Emerging from the grimy, broken-glass decay of 1970s New York City, the Ramones stripped rock and roll down to its absolute, blistering bare essentials. They brutally eliminated everything resembling 1970s indulgence: no soaring guitar solos, absolutely no songs over two and a half minutes, and only the fastest, most repetitive downstroke barré chords humanly possible.\n\nWearing identical torn leather jackets, ripped jeans, and adopting a unified, fake surname, they visually and sonically defined the absolute blueprint of American punk rock. Joey Ramone's towering, incredibly awkward frame and surprisingly melodic, 1960s-girl-group-inspired vocal delivery contrasted perfectly with Johnny Ramone's buzzsaw, machine-gun guitar playing.\n\nPlaying fiercely fast sets at the legendary CBGB club, they sang about sniffing glue, teenage lobotomies, and B-movie horror films with a bizarre, deadpan bubblegum sweetness. When they toured England in 1976, their gig effectively ignited the entire British punk movement, deeply inspiring bands like The Clash and the Sex Pistols.\n\nThough they rarely achieved massive radio or commercial success during their decades of touring, they are arguably the most influential American rock band of the last fifty years. They created a perfectly packaged aesthetic and sound that influenced almost every alternative pop and punk band that followed, from Green Day to Nirvana.\n\nThe Ramones proved definitively that you didn't need classical training or complex equipment to change the world—you just needed three chords, maximum volume, and the pure, stupid energy to play them really, really fast.",
